Posted @withregram • @contrarywestern @shifty71 was ramblin’ through town this past week and we had the chance to catch up with him yesterday before seeing him at @theryman opening for @blackberrysmoke .  As coast-to-coast as it gets from Los Angeles to Nashville, we tackled everything from the influence of Merle Haggard and the Bakersfield sound to the inspiration Chris has drawn from the Nashville musicians he worked with for his forthcoming record—while also drawing some pretty profound lines to the unbroken circles that make up the Venn diagram of punk rock and country music.
 Stay tuned these next few months to catch a few sessions from our time with Chris at @3sirens, which feature a cover of Merle Haggard’s “Ramblin’ Fever” and some new tunes accompanied by the finely featuring @foxfagan and @jollydrum.

Just announced: CHRIS SHIFLETT (of the FOO FIGHTERS) with special guest JIM LINDBERG (PENNYWISE), at FITZGERALDS SIDEBAR 9/14. Tickets on sale this Friday, 10am on our website! 

“Punk veteran. Rock & Roll Hall of Fame inductee. Americana and rock songwriter. Modern day guitar hero… For more than 25 years, Chris Shiflett has blurred the lines between genre and generation, balancing his full-band projects with a thriving solo career.
He turns a new page now with Lost at Sea, a solo record that builds a bridge between Nashville — where Shiflett has become a frequent visitor, performing on the Grand Ole Opry one minute and collaborating with Music City tastemakers like The Cadillac Three frontman Jaren Johnston and legendary producer Dave Cobb the next — and his native California.

Most known for his role as songwriter and lead singer of punk rock band PENNYWISE, Jim Lindberg has been making inspiring, shout-along skate punk anthems since the 1990s. Musically, he’s influenced by an array of genres from early Hermosa Beach melodic hardcore to the PMA influenced sounds of Minor Threat, 7 Seconds, and Dag Nasty. Lyrically, Jim has often taken inspiration from transcendental philosophers to produce not only heartfelt songs about self-reliance and individualism but also scathing indictments of political hypocrisy and corruption.”
